I would like to see the question focused on a purely legal and
educational ground.  That is to say, approach it from the current
debates in the public schools.

Many school districts are arguing for the inclusion of religious-based
understandings of the origin of human, other animal, and plant life
and origins the universe.  These alternate understandings are often
called Intelligent Design or Creationism to varying degrees.
Understandings of these same origins from the perspectives of
evolution and abiogenesis have a substantial amount of scientific data
to support them as verifiable scientific theories to help us
understand the origins and development of life.  It would seem that
any basis for these origins other than that which is strictly on clear
scientific grounds would be a clear confusion of something inherently
religious with the role of a public educational institution as one
that serves the ends of the state.  Moreover, clear problems with both
intelligent design and creationism are that neither can be supported
by scientific evidence or a scientific method to yield a scientific
result.  It would thus seem that either of these understandings would
yield confusion in the study of science itself in a science classroom.

What are the constitutional justifications for including any theory of
the origins of life and the cosmos that is directly related to any
religious understanding of these origins such as creationism or
intelligent design?  If there are clear constitutional reasons for the
former question, what are the scientific reasons that you understand
for any inclusion of intelligent design or creationism or any other
religiously based understanding of the origins of life and the
universe in the science classroom?

