This is why I think the questions needs to be focused on what someone
in a legal position can affect: the constitutionality of including any
understanding of the nature of reality that has clear religious
justification and also, the implications for including something in a
science classroom that is not scientific by its nature.  teaching good
science means teaching good hypothesis building and theorizing.  You
cannot do either of these with ID or creationism that by their nature
lack this level of investigation and methodology.  Now including them
in the vein of saying, here's why these theories are NOT science might
be good, but it is not even pretending that they are viable
alternative theories to origins because they are not actually
theories.  In a science classroom, the responsibility is to teach kids
good science, how to think like scientists, and to do good science.
Especially for the novice, confusing science with anything that is
only tangentially science at best does a disservice to that central
pedagogical outcome.

